{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512899"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11972"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11972"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.8,0.07,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66685"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11972"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1279"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"6169"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43284"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66685"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of right elbow pain. She works as a carpenter and reports the pain has gradually worsened, particularly when using power tools and lifting timber. The pain radiates down her forearm and is aggravated by gripping objects and turning doorknobs. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has tried over-the-counter anti-inflammatory medications with minimal relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Active and passive range of motion of the elbow is full but painful. Pain is reproduced with resisted wrist extension and forearm supination. Neck examination reveals full range of motion. Upper limb neurological examination demonstrates normal power, reflexes and sensation in all myotomes and dermatomes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical radiculopathy","Lateral epicondylitis","Posterior interosseous nerve syndrome","Radial tunnel syndrome","Triceps tendinopathy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral epicondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E in an occupational context. The condition is characterised by pain over the lateral epicondyle that is exacerbated by activities involving wrist extension and gripping. \u003Cstrong\u003ELateral epicondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects the dominant arm and is common in occupations requiring repetitive forearm pronation and supination, such as carpentry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical radiculopathy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause arm pain but typically presents with neck pain and neurological symptoms in a dermatomal distribution. The normal neurological examination and absence of neck pain make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior interosseous nerve syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a compression neuropathy causing weakness of finger and thumb extension without sensory changes. This patient has normal power throughout the upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to lateral epicondylitis but typically causes pain over the proximal forearm rather than the lateral epicondyle. Maximum tenderness is usually found 4-5 cm distal to the lateral epicondyle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriceps tendinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E causes posterior elbow pain and would be tender over the olecranon rather than the lateral epicondyle. It is typically aggravated by elbow extension rather than wrist extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of lateral epicondylitis is primarily clinical, based on the history and examination findings. Key physical examination findings include reproduction of pain with resisted wrist extension (Cozen\u0027s test) and point tenderness over the lateral epicondyle. Initial management includes activity modification, ergonomic assessment, and physiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lateral epicondylitis commonly occurs in occupations involving repetitive gripping, lifting and forearm rotation","Pain with resisted wrist extension (Cozen\u0027s test) is a key diagnostic finding in lateral epicondylitis","Differential diagnoses include radial tunnel syndrome and cervical radiculopathy"],"references":["Nirschl RP. Elbow tendinosis/tennis elbow. Clin Sports Med. 1992 Oct;11(4):851-70. PMID: 1423702.","Smidt N, Lewis M, VAN DER Windt DA, Hay EM, Bouter LM, Croft P. Lateral epicondylitis in general practice: course and prognostic indicators of outcome. J Rheumatol. 2006 Oct;33(10):2053-59. Epub 2006 Aug 1. PMID: 16881095.","Gragossian A, Varacallo M. Radial Nerve Injury. [Updated 2022 Feb 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537304/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11972"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T18:50:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T18:51:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66685"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ